# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldo-leopold
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Aldo Carl Leopold was born to Aldo Leopold, a noted ecologist and employee of the United States Forest Service, and Estella Leopold in Albuquerque, New Mexico as the 4th of 5 children.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Leopold received a bachelor's degree in botany from the University of Wisconsin in 1941.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He enlisted in the Marines during World War II and served in the Pacific as defense counsel in courts-martial for soldiers who were charged with being AWOL.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] After his discharge, Leopold received MS and PhD degrees in plant physiology from Harvard University, studying under Kenneth Thimann.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He worked briefly for the Hawaiian Pineapple Company, and then joined the faculty of Purdue University in 1949.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] In 1975, he was appointed Graduate Dean and Assistant Vice President for Research at the University of Nebraska–Lincoln.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] In 1977, Leopold moved to the Boyce Thompson Institute for Plant Research (BTI) in Ithaca, New York as William H.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He is known for being a pioneer in the study of the plant hormone auxin, and later for work on desiccation tolerance in seeds and gravitropism.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He is the author, with Paul Kriedemann, of a widely used textbook on plant growth and development.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Seeds such as soybeans containing very high levels of protein can undergo desiccation, yet survive and revive after water absorption.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Leopold began studying this capability at BTI in the mid-1980s.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He found soybeans and corn to have a range of soluble carbohydrates protecting the seed's cell viability by forming a glassy state rather than drying completely.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Patents were awarded to him in the early 1990s on techniques for protecting "biological membranes" and proteins in the dry state.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Using the knowledge gleaned from studying the preservation of proteins in dry soybeans, Leopold developed a method to preserve peptide hormones like insulin in the glassy state so that they can be pulverized into a powder and inhaled by diabetics as an alternative to self-injection.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] His research on soybeans led to techniques that allowed insulin to be dried and later processed into an inhalable insulin, named Exubera by Pfizer.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Leopold was active in science and environmental issues from his retirement in 1990 until his death in 2009.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Leopold, along with Ed Oyer, Thomas Eisner, Jim McConkey and Mary Woodson, was a founding member of the *Preposthumous Society* who together founded Greensprings Natural Cemetery Preserve.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] Leopold was the first member of the society to use it.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He was the founding president of the Finger Lakes Land Trust in 1989, to preserve wild lands in the Finger Lakes region of New York.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He founded the Tropical Forestry Initiative in 1993, which developed new methods to restore tropical forest from grazing lands in Costa Rica, and remained active until 2015.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-carl-leopold] He was cofounder of the Aldo Leopold Foundation in 1982 to help people explore and apply Aldo Leopold's land ethic.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Born in Burlington, Iowa, on October 22, 1913, A.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Starker Leopold was the oldest son of noted conservationist Aldo Leopold and Estella Bergere Leopold.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] His siblings—Luna, Carl, Estella, and Nina—also contributed significantly to the conservation movement.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] As a result of his father's employment by the United States Forest Service, Starker spent his early childhood in Albuquerque, New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] When Starker was eleven years old, the Leopold family moved to Madison, Wisconsin, as his father took a faculty position at the University of Wisconsin in 1924.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] As Starker spent his early boyhood fishing on the Rio Grande River and hunting in the oak and prairie country of Madison, Wisconsin, he learned to feel secure in nature from a young age.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] It is clear that Starker's passion for nature was instilled during his childhood, spent with his distinguished father.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Another critical experience that developed Starker's mindset and opinions on nature was a guided hunting trip in northern Mexico’s Sierra Madre mountain system with his brother Carl and father Aldo in the winter of 1937 - 1938.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Starker experienced an ecosystem untouched by humans, with all its processes intact, which allowed him to gain insight into the beneficial and essential roles predators and frequent low-burning fire play in wilderness landscapes.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In 1938, he married Elizabeth Weiskotten when both were students at the University of California, Berkeley; the couple had two children—Fredric S., born in 1941, and Sarah Leopold, born in 1948.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Starker Leopold, died due to a heart attack in his Berkeley home.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] He was survived by his wife, two children, and three grandchildren.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] He received his B.S. from the University of Wisconsin in 1936, and then studied at the Yale Forestry School before transferring to the University of California, Berkeley, where he received his Ph.D. in Zoology in 1944.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] With the help of professors, Joseph Grinnell and Alden H.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Miller, and his specific interest in ornithology, he completed his dissertation research on the nature of heritable wildness in turkeys.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The findings in his research are credited as a major contribution to the understanding of wild avian biology and behavior.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] During his education, he worked as a junior biologist with the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Soil Erosion Service from 1934 - 1935 and as a field biologist for the Missouri Conservation Commission from 1939 - 1944.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] After receiving his Ph.D., he worked in Mexico for the Conservation Section of the Pan-American Union as Director of Field Research from 1944 - 1946.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] After working in Mexico for the Conservation Section of the Pan-American Union, Leopold returned to the University of California, Berkeley, in 1946 as Assistant Professor of Zoology and Conservation in the Museum of Vertebrate Zoology.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] He was promoted to Assistant Professor in 1952 and then Professor in 1957.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Starker was an accomplished, enlightening teacher who was easy going which had earned him admiration from his students.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In 1958, he was appointed Associate Director of the Museum of Vertebrate Zoology and became the acting Director of the Museum after the death of Alden H.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] He was Assistant to the Berkeley Chancellor for three years (from 1960–1963).
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In early 1967, he changed his affiliation to the School of Forestry and Conservation, where he was professor of Zoology and Forestry until his retirement as Professor Emeritus in 1978.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Additional positions at Berkeley included serving as the Director of the Sagehen Creek Field Station from 1965 to 1979.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Leopold retained this association until his death twenty years later.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Being an expert on population irruption, ecosystems, and hunting, Leopold understood that implementing management methods in National Parks was required to approach this issue.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In response, Leopold and the Advisory Board published Wildlife Management in National Parks, better known as the Leopold Report, in 1963.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Many of the ideas in the Leopold Report reaffirmed those promoted in the 1930s by Joseph Grinnell and his students George Wright and Joseph Dixon, who asserted that management practices must be implemented to preserve the park's original state.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] While Wright and his students' ideas had little influence during the 1930s, the Leopold Report greatly impacted public policy within the National Park Service due to the ideas being presented in the environmentally conscious 1960s.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] This series of additional ideas and recommendations was groundbreaking for the National Park Service as it was the first ambition to manage parks' visitors and ecology together.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The main concepts of the report surrounded the goals, policies, and methods of wildlife management in national parks.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] It was recommended that the current method of wildlife protection alone was unsatisfactory and that the goal of the parks should be to preserve or, where necessary, recreate habitats that support native species, along with the regulation of animal populations to prevent habitat damage.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In 1964, the Advisory Board and Leopold scrutinized the United States Fish and Wildlife Service's Branch of Predatory and Rodent Control for excessive killing of animals that have not caused damage or danger to the public.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] This report is considered one of the most critical and intense assessments of a United States federal agency regarding the responsibility of animal control.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The final evaluation completed by Leopold and the Board was on the National Refuge System's evaluation of the importance of national refuges in migratory bird conservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The recommendation included increasing the number of refuges, increasing financial support for existing refuges, and using these refuges for research and ecology education.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The concepts of the Leopold Report not only applied to managing wildlife in order to protect the natural ecosystem but also to predator control, controlled use of fire, and the inclusion of scientific research in decision-making.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Starkers' advisor role for the National Park Service continued when he chaired a 1969 meeting of the Natural Sciences Advisory Committee to discuss grizzly bear management at Yellowstone.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] The meeting was held to question the bear management program implemented to reduce the number of bear-caused human injuries, property damage, and fatal attacks related to bears' access to human food and garbage sources by removing troublesome bears.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In addition to the more than 100 scientific papers he authored, Leopold wrote five books during his life, he was working on a sixth at the time of his death.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] While his writings were not at the forefront in the scientific community, his later works started to focus less on research and more on developing public policy.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Leopold took ideas in the scientific community and launched them into political arena, forming many policies that still stand today.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] In addition to the more than 100 scientific papers he authored, Leopold authored five books during his life and was working on a sixth at the time of his death.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] Ecologists and wildlife biologists universally credit Starker Leopold with enhancing the credibility of science through his life's work in conservation, wildlife management, and education.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] His research and authorship, as seen in the use of the Leopold Report, profoundly shaped the current views of the role of human presence in the management of nature.
[src:aldo-leopold/a-starker-leopold] This ideology is still currently used as part of the National Park Service's mission of supplying rigorous and timely scientific information to park managers to continue the preservation of parks for future generations.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Located in the Albuquerque Basin, the city is flanked by the Sandia Mountains to the east and the West Mesa to the west, with the Rio Grande and its bosque flowing north-to-south through the middle.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] According to the 2020 census, Albuquerque had 564,559 residents, making it the 32nd most populous city in the U.S. and the fourth largest in the Southwest.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Albuquerque metropolitan area had 955,000 residents in 2023, and forms part of the Albuquerque–Santa Fe–Los Alamos combined statistical area, which had a population of 1,162,523.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque is a hub for technology, fine arts, and mass media.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It hosts New Mexico's primary international airport, Albuquerque International Sunport, and the state's flagship and largest university, the University of New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The U.S. federal government has a strong presence through Sandia National Laboratories, one of three laboratories of the National Nuclear Security Administration, and Kirtland Air Force Base, the largest installation in the Air Force Global Strike Command.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Nicknamed **ABQ**, **Burque**, and **Duke City**, Albuquerque is home to several historic landmarks, including over 160 sites listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Notable annual events include the Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta, the largest balloon festival in the world, the Gathering of Nations, the largest powwow in North America, and the New Mexico State Fair.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque is also known for its restaurant scene, which features both New Mexican and global cuisine, and as a center of New Mexican music and architecture.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Petroglyphs carved into basalt in the western part of the city bear testimony to a Native American presence in the area dating back many centuries.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] These are preserved in the Petroglyph National Monument.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Tanoan and Keresan peoples had lived along the Rio Grande for centuries before European colonists arrived in the area that developed as Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] By the 1500s, there were around 20 Tiwa pueblos along a 60-mile (97 km) stretch of river from present-day Algodones to the Rio Puerco confluence south of Belen.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Of these, 12 or 13 were densely clustered near present-day Bernalillo, and the remainder were spread out to the south.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Two Tiwa pueblos lie on the outskirts of present-day Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Both have been continuously inhabited for many centuries: Sandia Pueblo was founded in the 14th century, and Pueblo of Isleta is documented in written records since the early 17th century.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It was then chosen as the site of the San Agustín de la Isleta Mission, a Catholic mission.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Before colonization, Navajo, Apache, and Comanche peoples were likely to have set camps in the Albuquerque area, as there is evidence of trade and cultural exchange among the different Native American groups going back centuries before European arrival.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque was founded in 1706 as an outpost as *La Villa de Alburquerque* by Francisco Cuervo y Valdés in the province of Santa Fe de Nuevo México.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The settlement was named after the original town of Viceroy Francisco Fernández de la Cueva, 10th duke of Alburquerque, who was from Alburquerque, Badajoz in southwest Spain.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque developed primarily for farming and sheep herds.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It was a strategically located trading and military outpost along the Camino Real.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It served other Tiquex and Hispano towns settled in the area, such as Barelas, Corrales, Isleta Pueblo, Los Ranchos, and Sandia Pueblo.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] After gaining independence in 1821, Mexico established a military presence here.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The town of Alburquerque was built in the traditional Spanish villa pattern: a central plaza surrounded by government buildings, homes, and a church.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This central plaza area has been preserved and is open to the public as a cultural area and center of commerce.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It is referred to as "Old Town Albuquerque" or simply "Old Town".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Historically it was sometimes referred to as "La Placita" (*Little Plaza* in Spanish).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] On the north side of Old Town Plaza is San Felipe de Neri Church.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Built in 1793, it is one of the oldest surviving buildings in the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] After the New Mexico Territory became a part of the United States in the mid-19th century, a federal garrison and quartermaster depot, the Post of Albuquerque, were established here, operating from 1846 to 1867.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In *Beyond the Mississippi* (1867), Albert D.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] During the Civil War, Albuquerque was occupied for a month in February 1862 by Confederate troops under General Henry Hopkins Sibley.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] He soon afterward advanced with his main body into northern New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] During his retreat from Union troops into Texas, he made a stand on April 8, 1862, and fought the Battle of Albuquerque against a detachment of Union soldiers commanded by Colonel Edward R.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This daylong engagement at long range led to few casualties.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The residents of Albuquerque aided the Republican Union to rid the city of the occupying Confederate troops.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] When the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad arrived in 1880, it bypassed the Plaza, locating the passenger depot and railyards about 2 miles (3 km) east in what quickly became known as New Albuquerque or New Town.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The railway company built a hospital for its workers that was later used as a juvenile psychiatric facility.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Many American merchants, mountain men, and settlers slowly filtered into Albuquerque, creating a major mercantile commercial center in Downtown Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] From this commercial center on July 4, 1882, Park Van Tassel became the first to fly a balloon in Albuquerque with a landing at Old Town.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This was the first balloon flight in the New Mexico Territory.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Due to a rising rate of violent crime, gunman Milt Yarberry was appointed the town's first marshal that year.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] New Albuquerque was incorporated as a town in 1885, with Henry N.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Old Albuquerque High School, the city's first public high school, was established in 1879.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Congregation Albert, a Reform synagogue established in 1897, by Henry N.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Jaffa, who was also the city's first mayor, is the oldest continuing Jewish organization in the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Old Town remained a separate community until the 1920s, when it was absorbed by Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] By 1900, Albuquerque boasted a population of 8,000 and all the modern amenities, including an electric street railway connecting Old Town, New Town, and the recently established University of New Mexico campus on the East Mesa.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In 1902, the Alvarado Hotel was built adjacent to the new passenger depot, and it remained a famous symbol of the city for decades.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Outdated, it was razed in 1970 and the site was converted to a parking lot.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In 2002, the Alvarado Transportation Center was built on the site in a style resembling the old landmark.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The large metro station functions as the downtown headquarters for the city's transit department.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It also is an intermodal hub for local buses, Greyhound buses, Amtrak passenger trains, and the Rail Runner commuter rail line.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In the early days of transcontinental air service, Albuquerque was an important stop on many transcontinental air routes, earning it the nickname "Crossroads of the Southwest".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] During the early 20th century, New Mexico's dry climate attracted many tuberculosis patients to the city in search of a cure; this was before penicillin was found to be effective.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Several sanitaria were developed on the West Mesa for TB patients.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Joseph Hospital, two of the largest hospitals in the Southwest, had their beginnings during this period.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Influential New Deal–era governor Clyde Tingley and famed Southwestern architect John Gaw Meem were among those who came to New Mexico seeking recovery from TB.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The first travelers on Route 66 appeared in Albuquerque in 1926.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Soon dozens of motels, restaurants, and gift shops sprouted along the roadside.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Route 66 originally ran through the city on a north–south alignment along Fourth Street.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In 1937 it was realigned along Central Avenue, a more direct east–west route.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The intersection of Fourth and Central downtown was the principal crossroads of the city for decades.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The majority of the surviving structures from the Route 66 era are on Central, though there are also some on Fourth.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The establishment of Kirtland Air Force Base in 1939, Sandia Base in the early 1940s, and Sandia National Laboratories in 1949, would make Albuquerque a key player of the Atomic Age.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Meanwhile, the city continued to expand outward into the Northeast Heights, reaching a population of 201,189 by 1960 per the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In June 2007, Albuquerque was listed as the sixth fastest-growing city in the United States.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Census Bureau reported Albuquerque's population as 34.5% Hispanic and 58.3% non-Hispanic white.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] On April 11, 1950, a USAF B-29 bomber carrying a nuclear weapon crashed into a mountain near Manzano Base.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] On May 22, 1957, a B-36 accidentally dropped a Mark 17 nuclear bomb 4.5 miles from the control tower while landing at Kirtland Air Force Base.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Only the conventional trigger detonated, as the bomb was unarmed.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] These incidents were not reported as they were classified as secret for decades.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Following the end of World War II, population shifts as well as suburban development, urban sprawl and gentrification, Albuquerque's downtown entered a period of decline.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Many historic buildings were razed in the 1960s and 1970s to make way for new plazas, high-rises, and parking lots as part of the city's urban renewal phase.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] As of 2010, only recently has Downtown Albuquerque come to regain much of its urban character, mainly through the construction of many new loft apartment buildings and the renovation of historic structures such as the KiMo Theater.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] During the 21st century, Albuquerque's population has continued to grow rapidly.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] During 2005 and 2006, the city celebrated its tricentennial with a diverse program of cultural events.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The passage of the Planned Growth Strategy in 2002–2004 was the community's strongest effort to create a framework for a more balanced and sustainable approach to urban growth.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Urban sprawl is limited on three sides—by the Sandia Pueblo to the north, the Isleta Pueblo and Kirtland Air Force Base to the south, and the Sandia Mountains to the east.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Suburban growth continues at a strong pace to the west, beyond the Petroglyph National Monument, once thought to be a natural boundary to sprawl development.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Because of less-costly land and lower taxes, much of the growth in the metropolitan area is taking place outside of the city of Albuquerque itself.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In Rio Rancho to the northwest, the communities east of the mountains, and the incorporated parts of Valencia County, population growth rates approach twice that of Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The primary cities in Valencia County are Los Lunas and Belen, both of which are home to growing industrial complexes and new residential subdivisions.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The mountain towns of Tijeras, Edgewood, and Moriarty, while close enough to Albuquerque to be considered suburbs, have experienced much less growth compared to Rio Rancho, Bernalillo, Los Lunas, and Belen.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Limited water supply and rugged terrain are the main limiting factors for development in these towns.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Mid Region Council of Governments (MRCOG), which includes constituents from throughout the Albuquerque area, was formed to ensure that these governments along the middle Rio Grande would be able to meet the needs of their rapidly rising populations.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] MRCOG's cornerstone project is currently the New Mexico Rail Runner Express.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque is located in north-central New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] To its east are the Sandia–Manzano Mountains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Rio Grande flows north to south through its center, while the West Mesa and Petroglyph National Monument make up the western part of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque has one of the highest elevations of any major city in the U.S., ranging from 4,900 feet (1,500 m) above sea level near the Rio Grande to over 6,700 feet (2,000 m) in the foothill areas of Sandia Heights and Glenwood Hills.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The civic apex is found in an undeveloped area within the Albuquerque Open Space; there, the terrain rises to an elevation of approximately 6,880 feet (2,100 m), and the metropolitan area's highest point is Sandia Crest at an altitude of 10,678 feet (3,255 m).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, Albuquerque has a total area of 189.5 square miles (490.9 km2), of which 187.7 square miles (486.2 km2) is land and 1.8 square miles (4.7 km2), or 0.96%, is water.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque lies within the fertile Rio Grande Valley with its Bosque forest, in the center of the Albuquerque Basin, flanked on the eastern side by the Sandia Mountains and to the west by the West Mesa.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Located in central New Mexico, the city also has noticeable influences from the adjacent Colorado Plateau semi-desert, New Mexico Mountains forested with juniper and pine, and Southwest plateaus and plains steppe ecoregions, depending on where one is located.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque has one of the highest and most varied elevations of any major city in the United States, though the effects of this are greatly tempered by its southwesterly continental position.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The elevation of the city ranges from 4,949 feet (1,508 m) above sea level near the Rio Grande (in the Valley) to 6,165 feet (1,879 m) in the foothill areas of Sandia Heights.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] At the Albuquerque International Sunport, the elevation is 5,355 feet (1,632 m) above sea level.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Rio Grande is classified, like the Nile, as an "exotic" river.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The New Mexico portion of the Rio Grande lies within the Rio Grande Rift Valley, bordered by a system of faults, including those that lifted up the adjacent Sandia and Manzano Mountains, while lowering the area where the life-sustaining Rio Grande now flows.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque lies in the Albuquerque Basin, a portion of the Rio Grande rift.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Sandia Mountains are the predominant geographic feature visible in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] *Sandía* is Spanish for "watermelon", and is popularly believed to be a reference to the brilliant pink and green coloration of the mountains at sunset.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The pink is due to large exposures of granodiorite cliffs, and the green is due to large swaths of conifer forests.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque lies at the northern edge of the Chihuahuan Desert transitioning into the Colorado Plateau.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Sandia Mountains represent the northern edge of the Arizona/New Mexico Mountains ecoregion.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The environments of Albuquerque include the Rio Grande bosque, (floodplain cottonwood forest), arid scrub, and mesas that turn into the Sandia foothills in the east.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Rio Grande's bosque has been significantly reduced and its natural flood cycle disrupted by dams built further upstream.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] A corridor of bosque surrounding the river within the city has been preserved as Rio Grande Valley State Park.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] A few remaining natural arroyos provide riparian habitat within the city, though natural arroyos draining into the Rio Grande have largely been replaced with concrete channels.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] After a series of floods in the 1950s, passage of the "Arroyo Flood Control Act of 1963" provided for the construction of a series of concrete diversion channels.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The network of channels was built by the Army Corps of Engineers during the 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Iconic urban wildlife includes the roadrunner, Gunnison's prairie dog, coyote, and New Mexico whiptail lizard.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The bosque is a popular destination for wildlife viewing, with opportunities to see porcupines and sandhill cranes in the winter.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Cooper's hawks are common in city parks.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The foothill open space at the eastern border of the city limits also features Sonoran scrub oak, with gray oak and some Colorado piñon trees in more mesic locations.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Desert willow is a native tree along some arroyos, and they are now commonly planted throughout the city; western honey mesquite and netleaf hackberry occur in small numbers beyond developed areas, as do remaining stands of creosote bush on the southern edge of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Tumbleweeds are a common weed in disturbed areas, and are used by Albuquerque's flood control authority, to make an annual holiday snowman adjacent to their headquarters building, near the "Big-I" interchange near the city's center.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque is geographically divided into four unequal quadrants that are officially part of mailing addresses, placed immediately after the street name.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] They are Northeast (NE), Northwest (NW), Southeast (SE), and Southwest (SW).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque's official quadrant system uses Central Ave for the north–south division and the railroad tracks for the east–west division.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] I-25 and I-40 are also sometimes used informally to divide the city into quadrants.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This quadrant has been experiencing a housing expansion since the late 1950s.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It abuts the base of the Sandia Mountains and contains portions of the foothills neighborhoods, which are significantly higher in elevation than the rest of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Running from Central Ave and the Railrunner tracks to the Sandia Peak Aerial Tram, this is the largest quadrant both geographically and by population.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Martineztown, the Maxwell Museum of Anthropology, University of New Mexico, the Uptown area, which includes three shopping malls (Coronado Center, ABQ Uptown, and Winrock Town Center), Hoffmantown, Journal Center, and Cliff's Amusement Park are all in this quadrant.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Some of the most affluent neighborhoods in the city are here, including: High Desert, Tanoan, Sandia Heights, and North Albuquerque Acres.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Parts of Sandia Heights and North Albuquerque Acres are outside the city limits proper.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] A few houses in the farthest reach of this quadrant lie in the Cibola National Forest, just over the line into Sandoval County.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This quadrant contains historic Old Town Albuquerque, which dates to the 18th century, as well as the Indian Pueblo Cultural Center.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The area has a mixture of commercial districts and low to high-income neighborhoods.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Northwest Albuquerque includes the largest section of Downtown, Rio Grande Nature Center State Park and the Bosque ("woodlands"), Petroglyph National Monument, Double Eagle II Airport, the Paradise Hills neighborhood, Taylor Ranch, and Cottonwood Mall.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This quadrant also contains the North Valley settlement, outside the city limits, which has some expensive homes and small ranches along the Rio Grande.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The city of Albuquerque engulfs the village of Los Ranchos de Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] A small portion of the rapidly developing area on the west side of the river south of the Petroglyphs, known as the "West Mesa" or "Westside", consisting primarily of traditional residential subdivisions, also extends into this quadrant.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The city proper is bordered on the north by the North Valley, the village of Corrales, and the city of Rio Rancho.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Four Hills neighborhood is located in the foothills of Southeast Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Volterra subdivision lies west of Four Hills.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Popular urban neighborhoods that can be found in Southeast Albuquerque include Nob Hill, Ridgecrest, Parkland Hills, Hyder Park, and University Heights.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Traditionally consisting of agricultural and rural areas and suburban neighborhoods, the Southwest quadrant comprises the south-end of Downtown Albuquerque, the Barelas neighborhood, the rapidly growing west side, and the community of South Valley, New Mexico, often called "The South Valley".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The quadrant extends all the way to the Isleta Indian Reservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Newer suburban subdivisions on the West Mesa near the southwestern city limits join homes of older construction, some dating as far back as the 1940s.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This quadrant includes the old communities of Atrisco, Los Padillas, Huning Castle, Kinney, Westgate, Westside, Alamosa, Mountainview, and Pajarito.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Bosque ("woodlands"), the National Hispanic Cultural Center, the Rio Grande Zoo, and Tingley Beach are also here.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] A new adopted development plan, the Santolina Master Plan, will extend development on the west side past 118th Street SW to the edge of the Rio Puerco Valley and house 100,000 by 2050.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque's climate is classified as a cold semi-arid climate (*BSk*) according to the Köppen climate classification system, while the Biota of North America Program and the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Geological Survey describe it as warm temperate semi-desert.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque is located near the crossroads of several ecoregions.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, the city is located in the southeastern edge of the Arizona/New Mexico Plateau, with the Arizona/New Mexico Mountains ecoregion defining the adjacent Sandia-Manzano mountains, including the foothills in the eastern edges of the city limits, above Juan Tabo Boulevard.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The eastern portion of the greater Albuquerque area is known as the East Mountain area, and it is within the Southwestern Tablelands, sometimes considered a southern extension of the central high plains or northeast New Mexico highlands.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] To the north is the Southern Rockies ecoregion in the Jemez Mountains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The average annual precipitation is less than half of evaporation supporting an arid climate (*BWk*), according to a more recent application of the Köppen climate classification system using over a century of climatology, with no month's daily mean temperature averaging below freezing.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The climate is mild compared to many parts of the continent farther north or east, protected by mountains and surrounding highlands.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] However, due to the city's high elevation, low temperatures in winter often dip below freezing.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Varied terrain and elevations within the city and outlying areas cause daily temperature differentials to vary.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque's climate is usually sunny and dry, with an average of 3,415 sunshine hours per year.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Brilliant sunshine defines the region, averaging 278 days a year; periods of variably mid and high-level cloudiness temper the sun, mostly during the cooler months.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Extended cloudiness lasting longer than two or three days is rare.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] December, the coolest month, averages 36.9 °F (2.7 °C); the median or normal coolest temperature of the year is 12 °F (−11 °C), while the average or mean is about 11 °F (−12 °C).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It is typical for daily low temperatures in much of December to mid-February to be below freezing, with a long-term average of 93 days per year falling to or below freezing, and two days failing to rise above freezing.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] By March, stronger winds occur on many afternoons, as temperatures warm with the change to spring weather patterns and storm systems pass to the north.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Spring can occasionally bring unsettled weather with rain or even light accumulations of snowfall, into early April, though spring is often the driest part of the year in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Late March and April tend to experience many days with the wind blowing at 20 to 30 mph (32 to 48 km/h), and afternoon gusts can produce periods of blowing sand and dust.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In May, the winds tend to subside as a summer-like airmass begins to occur, with a regularity of higher temperatures.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The warming and drying trend continues into June by mid-June, temperatures can exceed 100 °F (38 °C) for a brief period.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Summer is lengthy and very warm to hot, but except for midday through evening, they are tolerable for most people because of low humidity and air movement.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The exception is usually during the New Mexico monsoon, especially in July and August, when the dewpoint and relative humidity remain higher.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] 2.6 days of 100 °F (38 °C) or warmer highs occur annually on average, mostly in June and July and rarely in August due in part to the monsoon; an average of 64 days experience 90 °F (32 °C) or warmer highs.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Despite the rarity of such heat, 28 days with highs at or above 100 °F (38 °C) occurred in the summer of 1980 at Albuquerque's Sunport.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In mid-September, the monsoon begins to weaken.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Portions of the valley and West Mesa locations experience more high temperatures above 90 °F (32 °C) and 100 °F (38 °C) as part of normal or extreme weather each summer.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Autumn is generally cool in the mornings and nights but sees less rain than summer, though the weather can be more unsettled closer to winter, as colder airmasses and weather patterns build in from the north and northwest with more frequency.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Some years, a storm in November may cause a snow accumulation of one to two inches.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Precipitation averages 8.84 inches (225 mm) per year.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] On average, January is the driest month, while July and August are the wettest months, as a result of shower and thunderstorm activity produced by the monsoon prevalent over the Southwestern United States.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Most rain occurs during the late summer monsoon season, typically starting in early June and ending in mid-September.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque averages 7.9 inches (20 cm) of snow per winter, and experiences several accumulating snow events each season.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Locations in the Northeast Heights and foothills tend to receive more snowfall due to each region's higher elevation and proximity to the mountains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] East Mountain communities average more snow and at times not usually experienced in the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The metro area was one of several in the region experiencing a severe winter storm on December 28–30, 2006, with locations in the Albuquerque area receiving between 10.5 and 26 inches (27 and 66 cm) of snow.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] More recently, a major winter storm in late February 2015 dropped up to a foot (30 cm) of snow on most of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Such large snowfalls are rare occurrences during the period of record, and they greatly impact traffic movement and the workforce due to their rarity.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Traveling west, north, and east of Albuquerque, one quickly rises in elevation, leaving the sheltering effect of the valley to enter a noticeably cooler and slightly wetter environment.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] One such area is considered part of Albuquerque Metropolitan Area, commonly called the East Mountain area, is covered in woodlands of juniper and piñon trees, a common trait of southwestern uplands and the southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque's growing season averages 208 days, which is the total consecutive days of low temperature above 32 °F (0 °C) between the last spring freeze and first fall freeze, based on 1991 to 2020 climatology at the Sunport.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The growing season can vary depending on local terrain or the year, and is shorter in colder locales of the valley, foothills, and especially the East Mountains; Sandia Park averages a growing season of 152 days.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Albuquerque's drinking water comes from a combination of Rio Grande water (river water diverted from the Colorado River basin through the San Juan–Chama Project) and a delicate aquifer that has been described as an "underground Lake Superior".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The Albuquerque Bernalillo County Water Utility Authority (ABCWUA) has developed a water resources management strategy that pursues conservation and the direct extraction of water from the Rio Grande for the development of a stable underground aquifer in the future.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The aquifer of the Rio Puerco is too saline to be cost-effectively used for drinking.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Much of the rainwater Albuquerque receives does not recharge its aquifer.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] It is diverted through a network of paved channels and arroyos, and empties into the Rio Grande.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Of the 62,780 acre-feet (77,440,000 m3) per year of the water in the upper Colorado River basin entitled to municipalities in New Mexico by the Upper Colorado River Basin Compact, Albuquerque owns 48,200.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The water is delivered to the Rio Grande by the San Juan–Chama Project.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The project's construction was initiated by legislation signed by President John F.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Kennedy in 1962, and was completed in 1971.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] This diversion project transports water under the continental divide from Navajo Lake to Lake Heron on the Rio Chama, a tributary of the Rio Grande.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] In the past much of this water was resold to downstream owners in Texas.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] These arrangements ended in 2008 with the completion of the ABCWUA's Drinking Water Supply Project.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The ABCWUA's Drinking Water Supply Project uses a system of adjustable-height dams to skim water from the Rio Grande into sluices that lead to water treatment facilities for direct conversion to potable water.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Some water is allowed to flow through central Albuquerque, mostly to protect the endangered Rio Grande silvery minnow.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Treated effluent water is recycled into the Rio Grande south of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] The ABCWUA expects river water to comprise up to seventy percent of its water budget in 2060.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] Groundwater will constitute the remainder.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p01] One of the policies of the ABCWUA's strategy is the acquisition of additional river water.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Residents of the city are known as *Burqueños* (masculine grammatical gender) or *Burqueñas* (feminine grammatical gender), or more rarely as simply "Albuquerqueans".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Spanish terms are from Chicano slang (Caló).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] "Burqueño" is also sometimes used as an adjective for anything related to that city, or to specifically refer to someone who identifies with the Burqueños New Mexico prison gang, or one of the barrios within Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Burqueños often speak New Mexican Spanish and Western American English.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] According to the 2020 U.S. census, there were 564,559 people and 229,701 households in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The population density was 2,907.6 inhabitants per square mile (1,122.6/km2), making Albuquerque one of the least densely populated large cities in the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2020, the racial makeup of the city (including Latinos in the racial counts) was 60.3% White, 4.5% Native American, 3.1% Black or African American, 3% Asian, 0.1% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, and 9.2% Multiracial (two or more races).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] About half of all residents (47.7%) were Hispanic or Latino, of any race while non-Hispanic whites accounted for 37.7%.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.02.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] For every 100 females, there were 94.4 males.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.8 males.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2010, the median income for a household in the city was $38,272, and the median income for a family was $46,979.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Males had a median income of $34,208 versus $26,397 for females.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The per capita income for the city was $20,884.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] About 10.0% of families and 13.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.4% of those under age 18 and 8.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque metropolitan area had 923,630 residents in July 2020.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The area includes Rio Rancho, Bernalillo, Placitas, Zia Pueblo, Los Lunas, Belen, South Valley, Bosque Farms, Jemez Pueblo, Cuba, and part of Laguna Pueblo.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] This metro is part of the larger Albuquerque–Santa Fe–Los Alamos combined statistical area (CSA), with a population of 1,171,991 as of 2016.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The CSA constitutes the southernmost point of the Southern Rocky Mountain Front megalopolis, with a population of 5,467,633 according to the 2010 United States census, including other major Rocky Mountain region cities such as Cheyenne, Wyoming; Denver, Colorado; and Colorado Springs, Colorado.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Of the residents of Albuquerque who are religious, the majority of them are Christian.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Reflecting its long history as a Spanish city, Catholicism is the largest denomination; Catholics are served by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santa Fe, whose administrative center is located in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Collectively, other Christian churches and organizations, such as the Eastern Orthodox Church and Oriental Orthodoxy, among others, make up the second largest group.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Baptists form the third largest Christian group, followed by Latter Day Saints, Pentecostals, Methodists, Presbyterians, Lutherans and Episcopalians.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Judaism is the second-largest non-Christian religion in Albuquerque; Congregation Albert, a Reform synagogue established in 1897, is the oldest extant Jewish organization in New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Islam is the next largest minority religion, with an estimated 3,000 to 5,000 adherents, representing 85% of the state's Muslim population.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Islamic Center of New Mexico is the largest mosque in Albuquerque, hosting daily prayers and activities for both Muslims and non-Muslims.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Sikh Gurudwara and Guru Nanak Gurdwara Albuquerque serve the city's Sikh population, while the main Hindu organizations are the Hindu Temple Society of New Mexico and Gayatri Temple.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] There are several Buddhist temples and centers throughout the city, representing different movements and schools, such as Zen and Soka Gakki.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Like many major American cities, Albuquerque struggles with homelessness, which has become more visible since the 2000s.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] According to Rock at Noon Day, a homeless services center, there were an estimated 4,000 to 4,500 homeless people living in the Albuquerque metropolitan area in 2019, with millennials and elderly accounting for the fastest growing segments.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque Public Schools spokeswoman Monica Armenta said the number of homeless children enrolled in district schools (meaning children from families that have no permanent address) has consistently ranged from 3,200 to 3,500.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Coordinated Entry System, a centralized citywide system used to track and fill supportive housing openings when they become available, shows that about 5,000 households experienced homelessness in 2018.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Homelessness is particularly concentrated around Downtown, and also in the International District off Central Avenue, which suffers from chronic urban decay and drug use.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque hosts the International Balloon Fiesta, the world's largest gathering of hot-air balloons, taking place every October at Balloon Fiesta Park, with its 47-acre launch field.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Another large venue is Expo New Mexico, where other annual events are held, such as North America's largest pow wow at the Gathering of Nations, as well as the New Mexico State Fair.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Other major venues throughout the metropolitan area include the National Hispanic Cultural Center, the University of New Mexico's Popejoy Hall, Santa Ana Star Center, and Isleta Amphitheater.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Other notable museums in Albuquerque include the National Museum of Nuclear Science & History and the Anderson-Abruzzo Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta Museum and more can be found here.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Located in Downtown Albuquerque are historic theaters such as the KiMo Theater, which is located across the street from the New Mexico Holocaust & Intolerance Museum, and the Albuquerque Little Theater.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Near the Civic Plaza is the Al Hurricane Pavilion and Albuquerque Convention Center with its Kiva Auditorium.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Due to its population size, the metropolitan area regularly receives most national and international music concerts, Broadway shows, and other large traveling events, as well as New Mexico music, and other local music performances.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Sandia Peak Ski Area, adjacent to Albuquerque, provides both winter and summer recreation in the Sandia Mountains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It features Sandia Peak Tramway, the world's second-longest passenger aerial tramway, and the longest in the Americas.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It stretches from the northeast edge of the city to Sandia Peak, the summit of the ski resort, and has the world's third-longest single span.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Elevation at the summit is roughly 10,300 ft (3,100 m) above sea level, or "ten-three".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is a hub for production studios, including Albuquerque Studios (now Netflix Studios Albuquerque), which Netflix has developed as a production hub in the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] NBCUniversal also has a sizable and expanding presence in the city, as do independent multimedia franchise studios.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Numerous works of fiction take place, either fully or in part, in the Albuquerque metropolitan area.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] These include *Albuquerque* (a 1948 Western), *Bless Me, Ultima*, *The Good, the Bad, and the Ugly*, *Breaking Bad* (along with its spin-offs *Better Call Saul* and *El Camino*), *Pluribus*, *High School Musical,* and Coyote vs.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city is referenced in Billy Mize's 1967 album *Lights of Albuquerque*, Jim Glaser's 1986 song "The Lights of Albuquerque", Neil Young's song "Albuquerque", and "Weird" Al Yankovic's song "Albuquerque".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Many Bugs Bunny cartoon shorts feature Bugs traveling around the world by burrowing underground.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Ending up in the wrong place, Bugs consults a map, complaining, "I knew I should have taken that left turn at Albuquerque." Failure to do so can somehow result in Bugs ending up thousands of miles off-course.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city is served by one major newspaper, the *Albuquerque Journal*, which, along with *Albuquerque the Magazine*, is distributed throughout the Southwestern United States and catalogued by the Library of Congress.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] *The Journal* is New Mexico's most widely circulated newspaper, and used to compete with *The Albuquerque Tribune* until 2008; today *The Journal* competes with *The Santa Fe New Mexican* and *Las Cruces Sun-News*.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque metropolitan area itself has other local periodicals, *Valencia County News-Bulletin*, *Rio Rancho Observer*, *Corrales Comment*, and the student newspapers of *The Lobo* at University of New Mexico and *CNM Chronicle* at Central New Mexico Community College.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is also home to numerous radio and television stations that serve the metropolitan and outlying rural areas.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is home to eighteen broadcast television stations, including KOB, KRQE, KOAT-TV, and KLUZ-TV, although most households are served by direct cable network connections.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Christian media outlets in the city include Trinity Broadcasting Network which owns the KNAT-TV signal, and independent Christian broadcasting exists on KAZQ.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Each of the Albuquerque metropolitan area's megachurches have media presence with broadcasts of their sermons, those include Legacy, Calvary, and Sagebrush.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Christian radio is found on FM and AM through KLYT, KSVA, KDAZ, KFLQ, and KKIM.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] One of the longest running AM broadcasts in the United States is an ABC News Radio station called KKOB (AM).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The first officially licensed FM radio broadcast in Albuquerque was KANW which mostly broadcasts the New Mexico music genre and NPR programming.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Performers such as Al Hurricane, Al Hurricane Jr, Lorenzo Antonio, and Sparx popularized New Mexico's Hispano and Native American folk genre by blending it with rockabilly, jazz, Western, Norteño, Latin pop, and rock music.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Berry named the center stage of Albuquerque Plaza the "Al Hurricane Pavilion".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Other forms of American popular music are represented on FM radio: contemporary hit radio is featured on KOBQ.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] During the 1990s, the urban contemporary music radio format had two major stations, on "KISS 97.3" KKSS and "WILD 106" KDLW.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] KISS 97.3 still exists today, though WILD has changed to a variety of formats.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In the 2000s modern rock stations focusing on alternative rock, nu metal, and adult contemporary music became popular in the city, including the FM station KPEK "100.3 The Peak".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] During this time, contemporary Christian music garnered success with KLYT, branded as M88 in its earlier days, due to the crossover of Christian rock and Christian hip hop with popular music.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Music groups based in Albuquerque include A Hawk and A Hacksaw, Beirut, The Echoing Green, The Eyeliners, Hazeldine, Leiahdorus, Oliver Riot, Scared of Chaka, and The Shins.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Talk radio has several outlets in the Albuquerque area.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Including a public radio station run by The University of New Mexico KUNM-FM, for conservative talk radio there is KIVA "The Rock of Talk" owned by Eddy Aragon, and KKOB has a Cumulus Media station affiliated with ABC News Radio.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] As for sports radio there is KNML "The Sports Animal" and KQTM "The Team".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] As a large and multicultural city, Albuquerque is home to a variety of global cuisines, in addition to local New Mexican cuisine.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Many local restaurants receive statewide attention, with several becoming chains; the city hosts the headquarters of Blake's Lotaburger, Little Anita's, Twisters, Dion's, Boba Tea Company, and Sadie's, most of which offer New Mexican fare.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] As the focus of the Middle Rio Grande Conservancy District, the city is punctuated by agricultural acequias that contrast with the otherwise heavily urban settings.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Crops such as New Mexico chile are grown along the entire Rio Grande; the red or green chile pepper is a staple of New Mexican cuisine and widely available in restaurants, including national fast-food chains.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque also has a burgeoning brewery scene.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta takes place at Balloon Fiesta Park the first week of October.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Although the global COVID-19 forced the cancellation of the 2020 event, The Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta successfully returned in 2021.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It is one of Albuquerque's biggest attractions.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Hundreds of hot-air balloons are seen every day, and there is live music, arts and crafts, and food.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The original architecture of *La Villa de Albuquerque* is referred to as the Territorial Style, it was revitalized as the Territorial Revival architecture.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Architect John Gaw Meem is often credited with this revival.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] John Gaw Meem is also credited with developing and popularizing the Pueblo Revival style, which was based in Santa Fe but received an important Albuquerque commission in 1933 as the architect of the University of New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] He retained this commission for the next quarter-century and developed the university's distinctive Southwest style.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Meem also designed the Cathedral Church of St.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Pueblo Deco architecture was derived from Pueblo and Territorial styles meeting the Art Deco movement, and it is richly featured in downtown Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque boasts a unique nighttime cityscape, personified in the lights of Albuquerque, a common motif in art and song.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city lights twinkle and glitter from views on Nine Mile Hill, it was among Elvis Presley's favorite views.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Route 66 era neon signs, and LED style versions of the neon-style are common throughout the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Many building exteriors are illuminated in vibrant colors such as green and blue.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Wells Fargo Building is illuminated green.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The DoubleTree Hotel changes colors nightly, and the Compass Bank building is illuminated blue.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The rotunda of the county courthouse is illuminated yellow, while the tops of the Bank of Albuquerque and the Bank of the West are illuminated reddish-yellow.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Due to the nature of the soil in the Rio Grande Valley, the skyline is lower than might be expected in a city of comparable size elsewhere, and it was used to highlight the low-lying architecture of heritage Pueblo and Hispano architectural styles.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque has expanded greatly in area since the mid-1940s.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] During those years of expansion, the planning of the newer areas has considered that people drive rather than walk.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The pre-1940s parts of Albuquerque are quite different in style and scale from the post-1940s areas.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The older areas include the North Valley, the South Valley, various neighborhoods near downtown, and Corrales.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The newer areas generally feature four- to six-lane roads in a 1 mile (1.61 km) grid.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Each 1 square mile (2.59 km2) is divided into four 160-acre (0.65 km2) neighborhoods by smaller roads set 0.5 miles (0.8 km) between major roads.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] When driving along major roads in the newer sections of Albuquerque, one sees strip malls, signs, and cinderblock walls.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The upside of this planning style is that neighborhoods are shielded from the worst of the noise and lights on the major roads.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Bernalillo County Library system consists of nineteen libraries to serve the city, including the Main Library, Special Collections branch (Old Main Library), and Ernie Pyle branch, which is located in the former home of noted war correspondent Ernie Pyle.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Old Main Library was the first library of Albuquerque and from 1901 until 1948 it was the only public library.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The original library was donated to the state by Joshua and Sarah Raynolds.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Old Main Library was recognized as a landmark in September 1979.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It was not until 1974 with the movement of the South Valley Library into a new building that the Bernalillo built and administered a public library.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Not long after, in 1986, the Bernalillo and Albuquerque government decided that joint powers would work best to serve the needs of the community and created the Albuquerque/Bernalillo County Library System.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Bosque is a major outdoor area of the city with numerous hiking and biking trails.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Sandia–Manzano Mountains and West Mesa also have many hiking trails, such as La Luz Trail and Petroglyph National Monument.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] According to the Trust for Public Land, Albuquerque has 291 public parks as of 2017, most of which are administered by the city Parks and Recreation Department.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The total amount of parkland is 42.9 square miles (111 km2), or about 23% of the city's total area—one of the highest percentages among large cities in the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] About 82% of city residents live within walking distance of a park.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Biological Park manages the ABQ BioPark Botanic Garden, ABQ BioPark Aquarium, Tingley Beach, and ABQ BioPark Zoo.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Amusement parks in the city include Cliff's Amusement Park and Hinkle Family Fun Center; there was formerly The Beach waterpark, which became a vacant lot on Desert Surf Circle for several years, until Topgolf made a driving range in the lot.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is home to over 300 other visual arts, music, dance, literary, film, ethnic, and craft organizations, museums, festivals and associations, and the state's capital Santa Fe is known for being a major arts city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] One of the major art events in the state is the summertime New Mexico Arts and Crafts Fair, a nonprofit show exclusively for New Mexico artists and held annually in Albuquerque since 1961.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Isotopes are a minor league affiliate of the Colorado Rockies, having derived their name from *The Simpsons* season 12 episode "Hungry, Hungry Homer", which involves the Springfield Isotopes baseball team considering relocating to Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] On June 6, 2018, the USL Championship division announced its latest soccer expansion club with New Mexico United, who play their home matches at Rio Grande Credit Union Field at Isotopes Park.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Having been home to boxing mainstays Brenda Burnside, Bob Foster, and Johnny Tapia, Albuquerque later became home to Jackson Wink MMA gym.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Several MMA world champions and fighters, including Holly Holm and Jon Jones, train in that facility.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The PGA of America offers Albuquerque golf tournaments with Sun Country Golf House, including the Sun Country PGA Championship and the New Mexico Open which have been hosted in the metropolitan area several times.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Roller sports are finding a home in Albuquerque as they hosted USARS Championships in 2015, and are home to Roller hockey, and Roller Derby teams.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] While no longer operating in an official capacity, the defunct Albuquerque Dukes minor league baseball team still has a major following, and the Major League Baseball organization is aware of the team's continued popularity.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Isotopes sometimes hold a Dukes Retro Night where they wear Dukes uniforms, and The Duke mascot continues to be an icon of the city.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is a charter city, exercising home rule as opposed to being directly governed by state law.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Its charter was adopted in 1917 and has been amended several times, most notably in 1974, when the municipal government was changed from a commission-manager system to its current mayor–council system.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Under this arrangement, power is divided between a mayor who serves as chief executive, and a nine-member council that holds legislative authority.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The current mayor is Tim Keller, who was elected in 2017.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The mayor of Albuquerque holds a full-time paid position and is directly elected for four-year terms.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Members of the Albuquerque City Council serve part-time, paid positions and are elected from their nine respective districts for four-year terms, with four or five councilors elected every two years.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Elections for mayor and councilor are nonpartisan.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Each December, a new council president and vice-president are chosen by and among council members.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city council has the power to adopt all ordinances, resolutions, or other legislation.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It meets twice a month in the Vincent E.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Griego Council Chambers of the Albuquerque/Bernalillo County Government Center.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Ordinances and resolutions passed by the council are presented to the mayor for his approval; if the mayor vetoes an item, the council can override the veto by a two-thirds vote of councilors.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Each year, the mayor submits a city budget proposal for the next year to the council by April 1, and the council acts on the proposal within the next 60 days.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque's judicial system consists of the Bernalillo County Metropolitan Court, which serves other municipalities and unincorporated areas in the county; the main Metropolitan Courthouse is located in downtown.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Judges serve in nineteen divisions and are subject to partisan elections by county voters every four years.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Police Department (APD) is the chief law enforcement entity within city limits; the unincorporated area of Bernalillo County is policed primarily by the Bernalillo County Sheriff's Department.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] With approximately 1,000 sworn officers, APD is the largest municipal police department in New Mexico; in September 2008, it was the 49th largest police department in the country, according to the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque serves as the county seat of Bernalillo County.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The City of Albuquerque and Bernalillo County share some social services, and have created a joint city-county commission called the Albuquerque Bernalillo County Government Commission (ABCGC).
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 1986, the City of Albuquerque and Bernalillo County governments entered the joint powers agreement that created the Albuquerque/Bernalillo County Library System.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Bernalillo County Metropolitan Detention Center opened in 2003 and was jointly managed by the City of Albuquerque and Bernalillo County until 2006, and fully managed by Bernalillo County from 2006 to present.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is New Mexico's principal economic center, accounting for half the state's economic activity.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city's economy is highly diversified, centering on science, medicine, technology, commerce, education, media, entertainment, and culture (particularly fine arts); construction, film production, and retail trade have seen the most robust growth since 2020.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is the center of the New Mexico Technology Corridor, a concentration of institutions engaged in scientific research and development, which in turn forms part of the larger Rio Grande Technology Corridor that stretches from southern Colorado to southwestern Texas.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city was also the founding location of MITS and Microsoft.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The federal government spends roughly $4 billion annually in research and development in and around Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Pursuant to the CHIPS and Science Act—federal legislation aimed at expanding domestic semiconductor manufacturing, research and development of new technology, and workforce training—the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Department of Energy announced plans to construct a new 100,000-square-foot technology incubator for companies, academia, and national laboratories, as well as a new platform for facilitating the development of tech startups among minority communities.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The governments of Albuquerque and New Mexico have sought to attract more private investment into technology startups.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Film studios have a major presence throughout New Mexico; Netflix maintains a major production hub at Albuquerque Studios.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] There are numerous shopping centers and malls within the city, including ABQ Uptown, Coronado, Cottonwood, Nob Hill, and Winrock.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Outside city limits but surrounded by the city is a horse racing track and casino called The Downs Casino and Racetrack, and the pueblos surrounding the city feature resort casinos, including Sandia Resort, Santa Ana Star, Isleta Resort, and Laguna Pueblo's Route 66 Resort.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is home to the University of New Mexico, the largest university in the state and the flagship of the state public university system.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Central New Mexico Community College is a county-funded junior college serving new high school graduates and adults returning to school.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque hosts several programs and nonprofit schools of higher learning, including Southwest University of Visual Arts, Trinity Southwest University, the University of St.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Francis College of Nursing and Allied Health Department of Physician Assistant Studies, and the St.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Norbert College Master of Theological Studies program.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Southwestern Indian Polytechnic Institute (SIPI) is in an unincorporated area adjacent to Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Ayurvedic Institute, one of the first Ayurveda colleges specializing in Ayurvedic medicine outside India, was established in 1984.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Other state and nonprofit institutions of higher learning have moved some programs into Albuquerque; these include New Mexico State University, Highlands University, Lewis University, Wayland Baptist University, and Webster University.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Several for-profit technical schools including Brookline College, Pima Medical Institute, Carrington College, National American University, Grand Canyon University, the University of Phoenix and several barber/beauty colleges have established their presence in the area.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque Public Schools (APS) is the school district covering all of Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Schools within APS include both public and charter entities.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Numerous accredited private preparatory schools also serve Albuquerque students.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] These include various pre-high school religious (Christian, Jewish, Islamic) affiliates and Montessori schools, as well as Menaul School, Albuquerque Academy, St.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Pius X High School, Sandia Preparatory School, the Bosque School, Evangel Christian Academy, Hope Christian School, Hope Connection School, Shepherd Lutheran School, Temple Baptist Academy, and Victory Christian.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Accredited private schools serving students with special education needs in Albuquerque include: Desert Hills, Pathways Academy, and Presbyterian Ear Institute Oral School.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The New Mexico School for the Deaf runs a preschool for children with hearing impairments in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Since the city's founding, it has continued to be included on travel and trade routes including the historic El Camino Real, Santa Fe Railway (ATSF), Interstate 25 (I-40), I-40, New Mexico State Road 45, and Albuquerque International Sunport.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is the second largest city in the United States (after Phoenix) to have at least two Interstate Highways, but no three-digit Interstates.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The interchange between I-40 and I-25 is known as the "Big I".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Originally built in 1966, it was rebuilt in 2002.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Big I is the only five-level stack interchange in the state of New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] There are six road bridges that cross the Rio Grande and serve the municipality on at least one end if not both.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The eastern approaches of the northernmost three all pass through adjacent unincorporated areas, the Village of Los Ranchos de Albuquerque, or the North Valley.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Two more bridges serve urbanized areas contiguous to the city's perforated southern boundary.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The state owns most of the city's rail infrastructure which is used by a commuter rail system, long-distance passenger trains, and the freight trains of the BNSF Railway.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] BNSF Railway operates a small yard operation out of Abajo yard, located just south of the César E.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Chávez Ave. overpass and the New Mexico Rail Runner Express yards.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Most freight traffic through the Central New Mexico region is processed via a much larger hub in nearby Belen, New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Amtrak's Southwest Chief, which travels between Chicago and Los Angeles, serves the Albuquerque area daily with one stop in each direction at the Alvarado Transportation Center in downtown.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Greyhound Lines and FlixBus offer intercity transportation services to the Albuquerque Metro Area as well as transportation to other cities around the United States.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The New Mexico Rail Runner Express, a commuter rail line, began service between Sandoval County and Albuquerque in July 2006 using an existing BNSF right-of-way which was purchased by New Mexico in 2005.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Service expanded to Valencia County in December 2006 and to Santa Fe on December 17, 2008.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Rail Runner now connects Santa Fe, Sandoval, Bernalillo, and Valencia Counties with thirteen station stops, including three stops within Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The trains connect Albuquerque to downtown Santa Fe with eight roundtrips per weekday.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The section of the line running south to Belen is served less frequently.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The primary mass transit system is ABQ RIDE, which operates a variety of bus routes throughout the city, including the Albuquerque Rapid Transit (ART) express bus service.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The central nexus for public transportation is the Alvarado Transportation System, which connects ABQ RIDE to Amtrak, Greyhound Lines, and the New Mexico Rail Runner Express commuter rail.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2011, the City of Albuquerque commissioned a study to develop a bus rapid transit system through the Central Avenue corridor, which accounted for 44% of all bus riders in ABQ RIDE.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Construction began in 2017 on Albuquerque Rapid Transit (ART), including dedicated bus lanes between Coors and Louisiana Boulevards.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] ART opened for service in November 2019 and was free to use until January 1, 2020.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque was one of two cities in New Mexico to have had an electric street railway; its horse-drawn streetcar lines were electrified in the early 20th century.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Traction Company failed financially in 1915 and the City Electric Company was formed in its place.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Despite traffic booms during the First World War, and unaided by lawsuits attempting to force the streetcar company to pay for paving, that system also failed later in 1927, leaving the streetcar's "motorettes" unemployed.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2006, under Mayor Martin Chavez, Albuquerque planned a "fast track" development of a "Modern Streetcar" project, which would run mostly in the southeast quadrant on Central Avenue and Yale Boulevard.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Funding for the $270 million system failed amid vocal opposition from some residents.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque has a well-developed network of trails, bicycle routes, and paths totaling over 400 miles.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] A 2021 study by Walk Score ranked it 26th out of 130 U.S. cities in bike friendliness, based on indicators such infrastructure, terrain, and connectivity.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2009, Albuquerque opened its first Bicycle Boulevard on Silver Avenue.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In 2015, the city adopted the "Bikeway & Trails Facility Plan" to invest in its bicycle infrastructure, including improving and expanding the existing system, adding new routes, and establishing bike sharing programs.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Albuquerque as the 28th-most walkable of the fifty largest U.S. cities, indicating below average performance in metrics such as access to public transit and proximity to people or amenities.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] A follow-up study a decade later ranked the city 73rd out of 130 cities nationwide, with a walkability score of 42.6 compared to an average of 48, classifying it as "car-dependent".
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is served primarily by the Albuquerque International Sunport, located 3 mi (4.8 km) southeast of the city's central business district.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] It is the largest airport in New Mexico and the state's sole international airport, serving over 5 million passengers per year.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The city owns and operates the much smaller Double Eagle II Airport, which is primarily used for air ambulances, corporate flights, military flights, charter flights, aviation training, and private flights.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] PNM Resources, New Mexico's largest electricity provider, is based in Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] They serve about 487,000 electricity customers statewide.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] In September 2021, PNM entered final merger talks with Avangrid, the U.S. subsidiary of Spanish power giant Iberdrola.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] New Mexico Gas Company, a subsidiary of Canadian utility company Emera, provides natural gas services to more than 540,000 customers in the state, including the Albuquerque metro area.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The Albuquerque Bernalillo County Water Utility Authority is responsible for the delivery of drinking water and the treatment of wastewater.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Trash and recycling in the city are managed by the City of Albuquerque Solid Waste Management Department.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque is the medical hub of New Mexico, hosting numerous medical centers.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] The University of New Mexico Hospital is the largest hospital in New Mexico with 628 licensed beds and is the primary teaching hospital for the University of New Mexico School of Medicine, the state's only medical school.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Albuquerque's other largest hospitals are Presbyterian Hospital (Presbyterian Healthcare Services) with 543 licensed beds, Raymond G.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Murphy VA Medical Center (Veterans Health Administration) with 298 beds, and Lovelace Medical Center (Lovelace Health System) with 263 beds.
[src:aldo-leopold/albuquerque-new-mexico-p02] Smaller specialty hospitals include the Heart Hospital of New Mexico and Lovelace Women's Hospital.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-legacy-trail-system] The **Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System** is a system of 42 state trails in the state of Wisconsin, covering a total of 1728 miles.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-legacy-trail-system] It was named after conservationist and influential University of Wisconsin professor Aldo Leopold.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-legacy-trail-system] The trail system was created on November 20, 2007, when Governor Jim Doyle signed Senate Bill 161, and dedicated on June 4, 2009.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-legacy-trail-system] The trails have features that enable users to learn about the surrounding ecosystems and environments.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] The **Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District** is a historic district in Albuquerque, New Mexico, which comprises a single block on the west side of 14th Street immediately south of Central Avenue.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] It is notable for its Craftsman/Bungalow-style houses and as the residence of noted naturalist Aldo Leopold.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] The district makes up the northernmost section of the Huning Place addition, which was platted in 1913 from a section of the large estate formerly belonging to merchant Franz Huning.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] The eight houses in the district, all of which are contributing properties, were built between 1913 and 1920.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] The district was added to the New Mexico State Register of Cultural Properties and the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-neighborhood-historic-district] Aldo Leopold's house at 135 14th St. is also individually listed on the State Register with reference number 1786.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The **Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm** is a historic farm on Levee Road in rural Sauk County, Wisconsin, United States.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property was acquired in the 1930s as a family summer retreat by the noted conservationist and writer Aldo Leopold and is the landscape that inspired his conservation ethic and the writing of his best-known work, *A Sand County Almanac*.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is now owned and managed by the Aldo Leopold Foundation, which provides tours and other educational programs on the property and the adjacent visitors center.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1978 and was designated a National Historic Landmark in 2009.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold began buying land here in 1935, acquiring more than 150 acres (61 ha) by the time of his death in 1948.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The family continued to acquire land until 1970, including a small island in the river.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The family then donated the property to the Aldo Leopold Foundation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is about 264 acres (107 ha) on the south bank of the Wisconsin River northeast of Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The property is roughly rectangular in shape, extending south from the river, and roughly bisected by Levee Road.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The foundation has a visitors' center about 0.5 miles (0.80 km) east of the property at the junction of Levee and Schemp Roads.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The farm is biologically diverse, with floodplain forest and marshland and former fields that have been restored to native prairie.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The principal built feature of the farm is the former chicken coop, set midway between Levee Road and the river, where Leopold spent his time; there is also a small outhouse nearby.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] The soil in the region is sandy, the result of deposition during the Cambrian Period that was reworked by the Wisconsin glaciation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold's writings on conservation and the environment were significantly influenced by this landscape.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] *A Sand County Almanac*, a compilation of his writings, is widely regarded as one of the most influential works on conservationism of the 20th century.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold-shack-and-farm] Leopold wrote the essay, "Marshland Elegy," in 1937 which warned that sandhill cranes could become extinct in Wisconsin and the upper Midwest as the species had dwindled to just 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:aldo-leopold/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
